{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535755","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535755"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:59:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:59:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15504"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15504"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.21,0.01,0.72,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8195"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61653"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8195","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8195"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15504"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47099"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"548"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4051"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19834"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19835"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30677"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61653"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a skin lesion on his left nasolabial fold that has been present for several months and is slowly growing in size. He reports occasional bleeding from the lesion. His medical history includes hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia, for which he takes regular medications. He is a non-smoker and works as an engineer on construction sites with significant sun exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 1 cm raised, pearly lesion with visible telangiectasia at the inferior aspect of his left nasolabial fold (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Morphoeic basal cell carcinoma","Superficial basal cell carcinoma","Trichoblastoma","Nodular basal cell carcinoma","Merkel cell carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of basal cell carcinoma (BCC), specifically the nodular subtype. The key features supporting \u003Cstrong\u003Enodular basal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E include the pearly appearance, raised border, telangiectasia, and tendency to bleed. The location in a sun-exposed area and the patient\u0027s occupational sun exposure are additional risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMorphoeic basal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically appears as a flat or slightly depressed, firm, scar-like lesion with ill-defined borders. It tends to be more aggressive and infiltrative than the nodular variant, but does not typically have the pearly, raised appearance seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperficial basal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E presents as a scaly, erythematous patch or plaque that is typically larger and flatter than nodular BCC. It is more commonly found on the trunk rather than the face.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrichoblastoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare, benign tumour of follicular differentiation that can resemble BCC clinically. However, it typically occurs in younger patients and lacks the characteristic telangiectasia and tendency to bleed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMerkel cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is an aggressive neuroendocrine skin cancer that typically presents as a rapidly growing, firm, red-to-purple nodule. The slow growth and pearly appearance in this case make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe nasolabial fold is considered a high-risk site for skin cancers due to its sun exposure. Treatment options for nodular BCC in this location include surgical excision with appropriate margins, Mohs micrographic surgery, or other destructive techniques depending on the size and exact location of the lesion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nodular basal cell carcinoma typically presents as a pearly, raised lesion with telangiectasia and occasional bleeding.","The nasolabial fold is a high-risk site for skin cancers due to sun exposure.","Slow growth and occasional bleeding are characteristic features of basal cell carcinoma."],"references":["Peris K, et al. Diagnosis and treatment of basal cell carcinoma: European consensus-based interdisciplinary guidelines. Eur J Cancer. 2019;118:10-34.","Telfer NR, Colver GB, Morton CA. Guidelines for the management of basal cell carcinoma. Br J Dermatol. 2008;159(1):35-48."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47099"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15504"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21165"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21165"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/lq2rjqWgSYbPBYCQvZo1eAU4mMlRJr.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/lq2rjqWgSYbPBYCQvZo1eAU4mMlRJr.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":533,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47099","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47099"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-16T08:56:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-16T08:57:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{